{"parse":{"title":"Kabbadion","pageid":39559463,"revid":747551318,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:252px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Alexios_Apokaukos.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Alexios_Apokaukos.jpg/250px-Alexios_Apokaukos.jpg\" width=\"250\" height=\"358\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Alexios_Apokaukos.jpg/375px-Alexios_Apokaukos.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/98/Alexios_Apokaukos.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"450\" data-file-height=\"644\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Alexios_Apokaukos.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The <i><a href=\"/wiki/Megas_doux\" title=\"Megas doux\">megas doux</a></i> <a href=\"/wiki/Alexios_Apokaukos\" title=\"Alexios Apokaukos\">Alexios Apokaukos</a> in the garb of his office, including a richly-decorated blue <i>kabbadion</i></div></div></div>\n<p>The <i><b>kabbadion</b></i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Greek_language\" title=\"Greek language\">Greek</a>: <span lang=\"el\">\u03ba\u03b1\u03b2\u03b2\u03ac\u03b4\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd</span>) was a <a href=\"/wiki/Caftan\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Caftan\">caftan</a>-like garment, of oriental origin, which became a standard part of court costume in the last centuries of the <a href=\"/wiki/Byzantine_Empire\" title=\"Byzantine Empire\">Byzantine Empire</a>.\n</p><p>The first known reference to the <i>kabbadion</i> occurs in the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Kletorologion\" title=\"Kletorologion\">Kletorologion</a></i> of 899, where it is mentioned as the dress of the barbarian (<i>ethnikoi</i>) members of the Emperor's bodyguard, the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Hetaireia\" title=\"Hetaireia\">Hetaireia</a></i>. It re-appears in the mid-14th century in the <i>Book of Offices</i> of <a href=\"/wiki/Pseudo-Kodinos\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Pseudo-Kodinos\">pseudo-Kodinos</a> as the standard ceremonial dress for almost all court members. Kodinos describes it as an \"<a href=\"/wiki/Assyria\" title=\"Assyria\">Assyrian</a>\" garment adopted by the Persians, clearly indicating a provenance from the Islamic world. It is therefore usually equated with the long, caftan-like and full-sleeved tunic worn by various Byzantine officials in depictions of the 13th\u201315th centuries. It fastened down the front and was worn with a belt. Its colour and decoration were determined by rank, as described by Kodinos; it was usually richly decorated with gold embroideries on the collar and on borders along the sleeves and hem, and could be adorned with pearls.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sources\">Sources</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Kabbadion&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Sources\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation book\">Parani, Maria G. (2003). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=r9gfY--ZVYgC\"><i>Reconstructing the Reality of Images: Byzantine Material Culture and Religious Iconography (11th to 15th Centuries)</i></a>. Leiden: Brill. pp.&#160;60\u201361. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-90-04-12462-2\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-90-04-12462-2\">978-90-04-12462-2</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Reconstructing+the+Reality+of+Images%3A+Byzantine+Material+Culture+and+Religious+Iconography+%2811th+to+15th+Centuries%29&amp;rft.place=Leiden&amp;rft.pages=60-61&amp;rft.pub=Brill&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.isbn=978-90-04-12462-2&amp;rft.aulast=Parani&amp;rft.aufirst=Maria+G.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dr9gfY--ZVYgC&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AKabbadion\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation encyclopaedia\">Patterson \u0160ev\u010denko, Nancy (1991). \"Kabbadion\".  In <a href=\"/wiki/Alexander_Kazhdan\" title=\"Alexander Kazhdan\">Kazhdan, Alexander</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Oxford_Dictionary_of_Byzantium\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"The Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium\">The Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium</a></i>. New York and Oxford: Oxford University Press. p.&#160;1088. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-19-504652-6\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-19-504652-6\">978-0-19-504652-6</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Kabbadion&amp;rft.btitle=The+Oxford+Dictionary+of+Byzantium&amp;rft.place=New+York+and+Oxford&amp;rft.pages=1088&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1991&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-19-504652-6&amp;rft.aulast=Patterson+%C5%A0ev%C4%8Denko&amp;rft.aufirst=Nancy&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AKabbadion\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li></ul>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Byzantine_imperial_flag,_14th_century,_square.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Byzantine_imperial_flag%2C_14th_century%2C_square.svg/22px-Byzantine_imperial_flag%2C_14th_century%2C_square.svg.png\" width=\"22\" height=\"22\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Byzantine_imperial_flag%2C_14th_century%2C_square.svg/33px-Byzantine_imperial_flag%2C_14th_century%2C_square.svg.png 1.5x